    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>From class&#xAD;room straight to cu&#xAD;bi&#xAD;cle</h1>
    <h2>A work-study pro&#xAD;gramme al&#xAD;lows ITE stu&#xAD;dent Azharia Nasir to gain work ex&#xAD;pe&#xAD;ri&#xAD;ence as a lo&#xAD;gis&#xAD;tics spe&#xAD;cial&#xAD;ist, while also pur&#xAD;su&#xAD;ing a diploma</h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-12"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210112/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-12">2021-01-12</a></time> -
        BY MARY WU

            <a href="/category/tag-268435458/en/sg">Business</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268490063/en/sg">Career</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268486559/en/sg">Logistics</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268490580/en/sg">Supply Chain Management</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268447461/en/sg">Transportation</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268491071/en/sg">Industries</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537243080/en/sg">Institute of Technical Education</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540321522/en/sg">Sitma (Norway)</a>     </section>

        <p>I’ve been get­ting con­stant sup­port and guid­ance from ITE and my lec­turer. They mon­i­tor my growth and en­sure that I’m on the right track based on the tasks I’m given at work. My lec­turer also vis­its my work­place to meet my men­tor/man­ager and to get a bet­ter sense of my work en­vi­ron­ment.</p>
        <p>MISS AZHARIA NASIR</p>
        <p>Stu­dent, Lo­gis­tics and Sup­ply Chain Man­age­ment Work-Study Diploma,</p>
        <p>In­sti­tute of Tech­ni­cal Ed­u­ca­tion Col­lege East</p>
        <p>Af­ter get­ting a Higher Nitec in Lo­gis­tics for In­ter­na­tional Trade from the In­sti­tute of Tech­ni­cal Ed­u­ca­tion (ITE) Col­lege East in 2018, it was only nat­u­ral for Miss Azharia Nasir to con­tinue pur­su­ing a WorkS­tudy Diploma ( WSDip) at the same school.</p>
        <p>“My teach­ers and friends at ITE mo­ti­vated me, say­ing they saw po­ten­tial in me to con­tinue in the field. It also helps that I have a rel­a­tive who stud­ied lo­gis­tics, so there’s some­one I can ap­proach for help or ad­vice,” says the 24-year-old.</p>
        <p>So, in April 2019, Miss Azharia en­rolled in ITE Col­lege East’s Lo­gis­tics and Sup­ply Chain Man­age­ment WSDip, a twoand-a-half-year course. Be­fore en­rolling in the pro­gramme, she short­listed sev­eral com­pa­nies for her work at­tach­ment and was ac­cepted as a lo­gis­tics spe­cial­ist at YCH Group.</p>
        <p>Her week cur­rently com­prises five-and-a-half days of work and study — school on Wed­nes­days and work on the other days. This split set-up gives her the best of both worlds: work ex­pe­ri­ence un­der a men­tor at YCH Group, as well as a salary, com­pany ben­e­fits and a sign-on in­cen­tive through Skill­sFu­ture — all while con­tin­u­ing her ed­u­ca­tion.</p>
        <p>She says: “If I work full-time, I won’t be able to get my diploma, and if I study full-time, I won’t get valu­able work ex­pe­ri­ence. An op­por­tu­nity such as this only comes once in a life­time.”</p>
        <p>Con­stant sup­port from lec­tur­ers</p>
        <p>As the WSDip is a struc­tured col­lab­o­ra­tion be­tween an ed­u­ca­tional in­sti­tute and a com­pany, ITE lec­tur­ers of­ten check on their stu­dents’ progress.</p>
        <p>Says Miss Azharia: “I’ve been get­ting con­stant sup­port and guid­ance from ITE and my lec­turer. They mon­i­tor my growth and en­sure that I’m on the right track based on the tasks I’m given at work. My lec­turer also vis­its my work­place to meet my men­tor/man­ager and to get a bet­ter sense of my work en­vi­ron­ment.”</p>
        <p>It is also en­cour­ag­ing, she notes, that although she is one of the youngest in the com­pany, she is given the op­por­tu­nity to take the lead in mak­ing de­ci­sions.</p>
        <p>At school, she says her lec­tur­ers are very pa­tient and will ex­plain con­cepts re­peat­edly un­til the stu­dents un­der­stand them. The lec­tur­ers also take stu­dent feed­back se­ri­ously and are quick to rec­tify any is­sues raised.</p>
        <p>Miss Azharia’s job en­tails in­ven­tory man­age­ment, one of her pet top­ics in school. Apart from learn­ing about the sys­tem she uses at work, she has also gained knowl­edge about sys­tems used by other com­pa­nies or ware­houses. As a WSDip stu­dent, she also needs to know the en­tire lo­gis­tics and sup­ply chain process from be­gin­ning to end, un­like full­time em­ploy­ees who need to fo­cus only on one area.</p>
        <p>There is also off-the-job train­ing to en­sure stu­dents ex­plore other ar­eas of the field. One of her du­ties is man­ag­ing meet­ings, which in­cludes go­ing through the pre­sen­ta­tion slides and meet­ing agenda be­fore brief­ing the team.</p>
        <p>Af­ter grad­u­at­ing in Oc­to­ber, Miss Azharia hopes to con­tinue work­ing at YCH Group, with a fo­cus on cold chain man­age­ment or e-com­merce. She also hopes to re­duce the phys­i­cal pa­per­work in lo­gis­tics, to make the in­dus­try more eco-friendly.</p>
        <p>Be­yond lo­gis­tics, ITE also of­fers WSDips in part­ner­ship with com­pa­nies from var­i­ous sec­tors. By learn­ing through do­ing, grad­u­ates will gain a head start in their ca­reer while pur­su­ing a recog­nised diploma.</p>

